SIMPLE: dragoon
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dragoon
<hw>Dra*goon"</hw> <pr>(dr⟦adot⟧*g⟦oomac⟧n")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>dragon</ets> dragon, dragoon, fr. L. <ets>draco</ets>
dragon, also, a cohort's standard (with a dragon on it). The name was
given from the sense <ets>standard</ets>. See <er>Dragon</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>((Mil.)</fld> <def>Formerly, a soldier who was taught
and armed to serve either on horseback or on foot; now, a mounted
soldier; a cavalry man.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A variety of pigeon.</def>
<rj><au>Clarke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dragoon bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
umbrella bird.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dragoon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dragoon
<hw>Dra*goon"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Dragooned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dragooning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To harass or
reduce to subjection by dragoons; to persecute by abandoning a place to
the rage of soldiers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To compel submission by violent measures; to harass;
to persecute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The colonies may be influenced to anything, but they can be
<qex>dragooned</qex> to nothing.</q> <rj><qau>Price.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lewis the Fourteenth is justly censured for trying to
<qex>dragoon</qex> his subjects to heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dragoonade</ent>⟦br⟧
